#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16500
#, no-c-format
msgid "Advanced Linuxrc Options"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16502
#, no-c-format
msgid "Linuxrc is a program used for setting up the kernel for installation purposes. It allows the user to load modules, start an installed system, a rescue system or an installation via &yast;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16507
#, no-c-format
msgid "Linuxrc is designed to be as small as possible. Therefore, all needed programs are linked directly into one binary. So there is no need for shared libraries in the init disk."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16513
#, no-c-format
msgid "Running Linuxrc on an Installed System"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16514
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you run Linuxrc on an installed system, it will work slightly differently so as not to destroy your installation. As a consequence you cannot test all features this way."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16521
#, no-c-format
msgid "Passing parameters to Linuxrc"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16523
#, no-c-format
msgid "Unless Linuxrc is in manual mode, it will look for an <filename>info</filename> file in these locations: first <filename>/info</filename> on the flash disk and if that does not exist, for <filename>/info</filename> in the initrd. After that it parses the kernel command line for parameters. You may change the <filename>info</filename> file Linuxrc reads by setting the <filename>info</filename> command line parameter. If you do not want Linuxrc to read the kernel command line (for example because you need to specify a kernel parameter that Linuxrc recognizes as well), use <literal>linuxrc=nocmdline</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16536
#, no-c-format
msgid "Linuxrc will always look for and parse a file <filename>/linuxrc.config</filename> . Use this file to change default values if you need to. In general, it is better to use the <filename>info</filename> file instead. Note that <filename>/linuxrc.config</filename> is read before any <filename>info</filename> file, even in manual mode."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16546
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>info</filename> file format"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16548
#, no-c-format
msgid "Lines starting with <literal>#</literal> are comments, valid entries are of the form:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16553
#, no-c-format
msgid "key: value"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16555
#, no-c-format
msgid "Note that <literal>value</literal> extends to the end of the line and therefore may contain spaces. <literal>key</literal> is matched case-insensitive."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16561
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can use the same key-value pairs on the kernel command line using the syntax <literal>key=value</literal> . Lines that do not have the form described above are ignored."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16567
#, no-c-format
msgid "The table below lists important keys and example values. For a complete list of linuxrc parameters refer to <link xlink:href=\"https://en.opensuse.org/SDB:Linuxrc\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16595
#, no-c-format
msgid "Advanced linuxrc keywords"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16602
#, no-c-format
msgid "Keyword: Example Value"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:16607
#, no-c-format
msgid "Description"
